========================================lab1===============
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>table grid</title>
    <style>
      body {
        background-color: rgb(231, 214, 214);
      }
      * {
        padding: 0;
        margin: 0;
        box-sizing: border-box;
      }
      section {
        position: relative;
        top: 80px;
        height: 100vh;
        background: linear-gradient(rgb(220, 182, 32),rgb(0, 255, 157),rgb(174, 14, 30));
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
        padding: 20px;
        gap: 10px;
        width: 550px;
        margin: auto;
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      div {
        background-color: rgb(255, 162, 0);
        color: rgb(249, 244, 244);
        padding: 10px;
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
      }
      #a1 {
        background-color: red;
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a2 {
        background-color: rgb(61, 116, 46);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a3 {
        background-color: rgb(21, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a4 {
        background-color: rgb(68, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a5 {
        background-color: rgb(68, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a6 {
        background-color: rgb(255, 174, 0);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a7 {
        background-color: rgb(68, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a8 {
        background-color: rgb(68, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
      #a9 {
        background-color: rgb(68, 0, 255);
        border-radius: 10px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <!-- grid-column and grid-row both are short hand props -->
    <!--"grid-column-start: 1; grid-column-end: 4"-->
    <section>
      <div style="grid-column: 1 / span 2" id="a1">
        item 1( Spans 2 Columns)
      </div>
      <div id="a4">item 2</div>
      <!-- grid-column : 1/4 ; is short hand prop for grid-column-start: 1; grid-column-end: 4 -->
      <div style="grid-row: 2 / span 2" id="a2">item 5( Spans 2 Rows)</div>
      <div id="a3">item 3</div>
      <div id="a5">item 4</div>
      <div style="grid-column: 2 / span 2" id="a6">item 9( Span 2 Columns)</div>
      <div id="a7">item 6</div>
      <div id="a8">item 7</div>
      <div id="a9">item 8</div>
    </section>
  </body>
</html>
=====================================================lab2=============================
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Fixed Sidebars Layout</title>

    <style>
      * {
        box-sizing: border-box;
      }

      body {
        margin: 0;
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        background: #e6e6e6;
        overflow: hidden;
      }

      header,
      footer {
        background: linear-gradient(45deg, red, blue);
        color: white;
        padding: 20px;
        text-align: center;
        font-size: 1.5em;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      footer {
        background: #444;
        font-size: 1em;
      }

      nav {
        position: fixed;
        top: 80px;
        bottom: 50px;
        left: 0;
        width: 200px;
        background: #444;
        color: white;
        padding: 20px;
        overflow-y: auto;
      }

      nav a {
        display: block;
        text-decoration: none;
        background: #666;
        color: white;
        padding: 10px;
        border-radius: 6px;
        text-align: center;
        font-weight: bold;
        margin-bottom: 10px;
        transition: 0.3s;
      }

      nav a:hover {
        background: #555;
      }

      aside {
        position: fixed;
        top: 80px;
        bottom: 50px;
        right: 0;
        width: 250px;
        background: #ddd;
        padding: 20px;
        overflow-y: auto;
      }

      .main-container {
        position: absolute;
        top: 80px;
        bottom: 50px;
        left: 200px;
        right: 250px;
        overflow-y: auto;
        background: white;
        padding: 20px;
      }

      @media (max-width: 768px) {
        nav,
        aside {
          position: static;
          width: 100%;
          height: auto;
        }

        header,
        footer {
          position: static;
        }

        .main-container {
          position: static;
          padding: 10px;
          overflow: visible;
        }

        body {
          overflow: auto;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <header>My Awesome Website</header>

    <nav>
      <a href="#">Home</a>
      <a href="#">About</a>
      <a href="#">Services</a>
      <a href="#">Contact</a>
    </nav>

    <div class="main-container">
      <h2>Welcome to Our Page!</h2>
      <p>
        This is a demo of a layout with fixed sidebars and a scrollable main
        area.
      </p>
      <p>Resize the browser window to see the responsive behavior.</p>
      <p>
        Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet consectetur adipisicing elit. Totam delectus
        atque consequuntur dolores aliquid tenetur rem quaerat, enim voluptates?
        Ex rem eveniet fugiat accusamus sequi, inventore suscipit voluptatum
        esse minima.
      </p>
      <p>
        Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet consectetur adipisicing elit. Itaque ab
        quidem quia error, blanditiis aliquam perferendis doloribus perspiciatis
        id? Est necessitatibus tempore alias nostrum delectus sint tempora quia
        possimus sunt?
      </p>
      <p>
        HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are the foundational pillars of modern web
        development, each serving a distinct yet interconnected role in creating
        interactive and visually appealing websites. HTML (HyperText Markup
        Language) provides the fundamental structure and content of a webpage,
        acting as the "skeleton" that defines elements like headings,
        paragraphs, images, and links using a system of tags. CSS (Cascading
        Style Sheets) is responsible for the visual presentation and styling of
        the HTML elements. It dictates the aesthetics of a webpage, controlling
        aspects such as colors, fonts, layout, spacing, and responsive design,
        transforming the raw HTML structure into a polished and visually
        engaging user interface. JavaScript adds dynamic functionality and
        interactivity to a webpage, bringing the static structure and styling to
        life. It enables features like animated elements, form validation,
        interactive maps, dynamic content updates, and complex user
        interactions, making websites engaging and responsive to user input.
        Together, these three languages form a powerful trio, allowing
        developers to build everything from simple static pages to complex,
        feature-rich web applications.
      </p>
    </div>

